      "body": "It seems to me one of the first steps here is to separate the library code from the test code better.  (Compile the library, then compile tests that link to that library from code in a separate directory)\r\n\r\nBroadly I see:\r\n* Conformance tests - Like OpenSSL to ensure that the cyrpto is correct, these are very good today\r\n* Performance tests - ensure that the operations are performant (handed by bench*.c and friends), these exist\r\n* Client tests - Build and sanity check that a consumer can accomplish it's task, needs work\r\n* (NEW) API tests - Do all the things that a client shouldn't do and make sure its gracefully handled.  Because of the nature of this it seems like the wise idea might be to use a language like python/ruby and FFI the API surface because it's easier to create a large matrix of tests this way.  It also tests that FFI works correctly (as much as I hate FFI ðŸ˜†)",
